## Three-Minute Story

**Situation.** A tier-1 credit-card issuer needed an AI-augmented payment system that could make millisecond fraud decisions, explain declines in seconds, and kick off automated triage within 10 seconds — all at 20,000+ TPS with strict tail-latency SLAs.

**Approach.** I designed a three-tier architecture. Tier 1 is a zero-copy Rust/CUDA scoring pipeline: per-core arenas, borrowed transaction views, shared feature blocks, an ensemble of XGBoost/GBDT/scorecard/neural models, and a binary Go/No-Go output — all within 5 ms p99. Tier 2 uses a fast reasoning model behind Sentinel to explain No-Go decisions within 2–5 seconds. Tier 3 uses a deeper agentic workflow behind Sentinel + Helios to dispatch triage actions within 5–10 seconds. The key integration is an Arrow-compatible shared event buffer that lets all three tiers consume the same transaction context without re-parsing or reserializing.

**Measurement.** I would validate with sustained peak loads, decline spikes, GPU replica failures, and slow downstream tools. The critical outputs would be p99 latency per tier, queue and degrade behavior under overload, cross-tier trace completeness, and the zero-copy overhead — bytes copied per transaction across the full pipeline.

**Learning.** The winning pattern is not "put AI everywhere." It is "keep the fraud decisioning path deterministic and zero-copy, then engineer the reasoning and triage layers with the same production discipline using Sentinel." The zero-copy investment pays off most at the tier boundary: publish once in Arrow, let reasoning, triage, logging, analytics, and retraining all consume the same physical bytes.

